{% block content %}



<p> It is very important to us that we promote inclusive events.
There are myriad methods of gender and sex identification, and there
are many issues regarding how people date and relate across and among
these lines.  We have therefore tried to avoid asking for
self-identification altogether!

<h3>Overview</h3>

You have to answer a <b>preference</b> question on whom you are
looking for, and a <b>minimal requirements</b> question about whom
your dates should be looking for.

<p>Usually, what you want your dates to be looking for is... you! So,
for example, men will click the box that says their dates should
be looking for men. You can require your dates to be
okay with additional gender categories as well.

We gauge whether others would be interested in you based on your
preferences.  When this works out both ways, we have a match.


<p>
On the form, there are two columns of checkboxes: what you are looking
for, and what you want your matches to be looking for in terms of
gender, sex, or presentation.
<p>

The first column is straightforward: check off what you want.  
<p>

For the second column, typically
people will check off their own identification since they
want their matches to be open to who they are.  So if a dater
identifies as a man, they would probably check off "men" and/or "trans
men" in the second column.
<!--  They may also check off other boxes, such
as "androgynous."-->

<p>
We phrase this question in a roundabout manner because we want to get
 away from questions of personal identity.  We instead allow people to
 say what is important to them in terms of what their matches are open
 to.  Also, getting away from identity opens up the possibility of
 neat dating tricks such as one described below in the examples
 section.
<p>

<!--<b>The rule used by the speed dating algorithm is: for a match to happen, everything in the other person's
 second column must be included in your first column (and your second column must include their first column too).</b>  
I.e., you must be open to every category that they request, and vice versa.
-->

The above can be summarized by the following two rules: </p>
    <b><p align="center"><em>You can only be matched with people who are looking
      for all the things that you check off in the second column.</em></p></b>
   and<b>
    <p align="center"><em>You will never be matched with people who have checked off a category in the second column that you are not looking for.</em></p>
</b>
<p>

So if someone marked off "women" and "genderqueer..." in their second
column, and you marked off "women," "trans women," and
"genderqueer..."  in your first column, then they could be a match for
you.  If you had only marked off "woman," then they would not be a
match for you because they want people open to genderqueer people and
you did not indicate you were open to such matches.

<p>
No problem, right?  One final note:
<B> <p align="center"><em>Don't say you are open to something unless
      you actually are!</em></p></B>  It is not fun for people to go
      on dates with people clearly not interested in them a priori.
 
<p>


<h3>Stating Preferences (The Double Check-Box)</h3>

Each entry in the first column has two checkboxes.  If you check off either one
of the checkboxes, it means that you are open to dating someone of
that gender or sex.  If you check off both checkboxes,
it means that you <i>prefer</i> to date someone in that category.  The
matching algorithm will score those matches higher and you will be
more likely to get them.  This can be used to set up situations with a
preferred set of genders and a fallback set of genders.  See the
example section below for some situations where this might be helpful.


<h3>Trans Sexes/Genders and Matching</h3>

There has been a lot of debat as to whether "trans" should have its
own checkbox.  Based on feedback from many trans people, we have
decided to have such a box.  It is entirely optional whether you use
it or not.  We encourage trans folks to do which ever of the following
feels most comfortable and true:
<ul>
<li>Check off an unmarked category ("men" and/or "women") only</li>
<li>Check off a trans category ("trans men" and/or "trans women") only</li>
<li>Check off both the marked and unmarked categories</li>
<li>Anything else that they find apporpriate</li>
</ul>

We have talked to some trans people who want to filter out anyone not
okay with their trans status, and so enjoy having the marked
categories as well as the unmarked categories.  But at the same time
we have talked to other trans people who prefer to date simply as
"men" or "women" as they feel that they should not have to mark
themselves as trans in any particular way.  This is also fine.  Note
that by checking off both categories, a trans man, say, could not be
"targeted" since a potential dater would have to indicate <i>both</i>
being open to trans men and men.  To be clear: we have these boxes
because many trans people have expressed a desire to have them.  It is
a tool to help trans people navigate speed dating in a way that feels
comfortable, safe, and worthwhile. 
<p>
Please read our more complete discussion of why we made these choices
in the design of the matching system <a href="{% url about-page
what="trans"%}">here</a>.


<h3>Intersex</h3>
<p> We currently do not have an &quot;intersex&quot; gender category.
      Reasons for that are discussed <a href="{% url about-page
      what="intersex"%}">here</a>.  In short, intersexed people may
      identitfy as one or multiple genders, and we hope they will fill
      their forms out accordingly.  We feel that the important thing
      to focus on for Poly Speed Dating purposes is what gender
      identity and presentations people are open to, which is why we
      have not made Intersexed a category choice. </p>


<h3>The presentation question</h3>

We have added another gender-like question which includes
"presentation-like" questions such as butch/femme/andro.  Currently
this is a preference-only question, allowing you to signal what you
want a bit better.  But we do not do hard matching on this question,
meaning we may schedule you for dates who are not looking for what you
indicate here.  We can only do so much!


<h3>Strategies and Examples</h3>

In general, checking off more categories in the first column gets a person more dates, and checking off fewer categories in
 the second column gets a person more dates. 

<p>
We encourage folks to check off anything they are okay with in the
first column, since one's first column picks must include all of a
potential match's second column picks.  So if person wants to date any
sort of man, then they should not just check off "men" and "trans
men," because that would exclude men who check off the other
categories as well.  Thus they might also check off  "genderqueer" and possibly "none of the above"  in the first column
to catch guys who have put any of those in their second column.  Of
course, this means they might get people who only identify as
genderqueer.  See how this gets tricky?


<p>
Here are some examples of trickier uses of the gender matching system:

<p>
1) <b>Man looking for bi men</b>.  Check off "men" and "trans men" in the first column (and probably some other categories), and "men" and "women" in the second column.
<p>

2) <b>Femme woman preferring butch women, but open to dating all women</b>.  Check off "women" and "trans women" in the first column with a single checkbox, and "butch" in the second question.  Check off "women" and "femme" in the second column.
